.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF54FF941D95FCB9999AFB05" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF54FF941D95FCB9999AFB05" blockId="9.[151,1437,577,1432]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF941D95FCB99974FCC9" bold="true" box="[199,322,829,855]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Larger (TL: 
<quantity id="664DB6BCBF54FF941C8EFCB99A5CFCC6" box="[476,618,829,856]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="5.7" metricValueMin="5.3" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="5.7" valueMin="5.3">5.3–5.7 mm</quantity>
), oblong-oval species. Head brown, with reddish clypeus and two oval spots on vertex; pronotum brown, laterally broadly orange, anterior and posterior margin orange translucent; elytra pale brown on disc, base and lateral sides yellowish brown. Pronotum with only several short longitudinal strioles laterally. Each elytron with six complete discal striae and one submarginal stria: all striae beginning at base; stria 1 longest, ending close to apex, odd striae somewhat longer than even ones; stria 6 shortest, ending at apical fourth; submarginal stria long, beginning before elytral mid-length and ending at apical fourth (
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF54FF9419DCFC759CE2FB95" box="[1166,1236,1009,1035]" captionStart="FIGURES 5–8" captionStartId="32.[151,264,1943,1967]" captionTargetBox="[239,1352,196,1907]" captionTargetId="figure-23@32.[221,1367,181,1920]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURES 5–8. Habitus of Copelatus in China. 5. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (holotype ♂; Pu’er, Yunnan); 6. C. diversistriatus sp. nov. (♂; NE Mintaingbin Forest Camp, Myanmar); 7. C. felicis sp. nov. (holotype ♂; Baishui, Yunnan); 8. C. japonicus (♂; Shanghai). Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6410704" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6410704/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Median lobe of aedeagus in lateral view simple, sickle shaped, strongly curved; broad in basal half and slender in apical half; apex pointed (
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF54FF941DA9FBBD9966FBCD" box="[251,336,1081,1107]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–50" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[210,1370,207,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-18@39.[192,1395,181,1815]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 39–50. Male genitalia of Copelatus. 39, 41, 43, 45, 47, 49. median lobe in lateral view; 40, 42, 44, 46, 48, 50. paramere. 39–40. C. japonicus (Shanghai); 41. C. malaisei (a. Gaoligongshan, Yunnan; b. Renjiafen, Yunnan); 42. C. malaisei (Renjiafen, Yunnan); 43–44. C. miaowangi sp. nov. (paratype, Liupanshui, Guizhou); 45–46. C. mopanshanensis sp. nov. (holotype, Mopanshan, Yunnan); 47–48. C. nanlingensis sp. nov. (holotype, Dadongshan, Guangdong); 49–50. C. oblitus (Macao). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6412781" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6412781/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
). Parameres slender, ‘C’-shaped; apex short and broad; apical lobes moderately long, club-shaped (
<figureCitation id="398E07DCBF54FF941DF2FBD998C3FBE9" box="[160,245,1117,1143]" captionStart="FIGURES 39–50" captionStartId="39.[151,264,1839,1863]" captionTargetBox="[210,1370,207,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-18@39.[192,1395,181,1815]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURES 39–50. Male genitalia of Copelatus. 39, 41, 43, 45, 47, 49. median lobe in lateral view; 40, 42, 44, 46, 48, 50. paramere. 39–40. C. japonicus (Shanghai); 41. C. malaisei (a. Gaoligongshan, Yunnan; b. Renjiafen, Yunnan); 42. C. malaisei (Renjiafen, Yunnan); 43–44. C. miaowangi sp. nov. (paratype, Liupanshui, Guizhou); 45–46. C. mopanshanensis sp. nov. (holotype, Mopanshan, Yunnan); 47–48. C. nanlingensis sp. nov. (holotype, Dadongshan, Guangdong); 49–50. C. oblitus (Macao). Scale bar 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6412781" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6412781/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Female similar to male; strioles on pronotum more numerous, microreticulation of pronotum and elytra slightly more impressed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF54FF941D95FB219CDCFAED" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF54FF941D95FB219CDCFAED" blockId="9.[151,1437,577,1432]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF941D95FB219A79FB21" bold="true" box="[199,591,1189,1215]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">Comments on the classification.</emphasis>
This Japanese species was recorded from several Chinese provinces by various authors (see 
<bibRefCitation id="C52466A8BF54FF941CD4FB4D9A2BFB7A" author="Nilsson, A. N." box="[390,541,1225,1252]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" pagination="35 - 96" refId="ref33005" refString="Nilsson, A. N. (1995) Noteridae and Dytiscidae: Annotated check list of the Noteridae and Dytiscidae of China (Coleoptera). In: Jach, M. A. &amp; Ji, L. (Eds.), Water beetles of China. Vol. I. Zoologisch-Botanische Gesellschaft in Osterreich and Wiener Coleopterologenverein, Wien, pp. 35 - 96." type="book chapter" year="1995">Nilsson 1995</bibRefCitation>
for summary), also under the names 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF54FF941E82FB4E9C6DFB7D" authorityName="Regimbart" authorityYear="1899" box="[976,1115,1225,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF941E82FB4E9C6DFB7D" box="[976,1115,1225,1252]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">C. chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF54FF9419C5FB4E9D78FB7D" authorityName="Falkenstrom" authorityYear="1933" box="[1175,1358,1225,1252]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="collocallosus">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF9419C5FB4E9D78FB7D" box="[1175,1358,1225,1252]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">C. collocallosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which were synonymized with 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF54FF941CFCFB6A9A0BFA99" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1884" box="[430,573,1262,1288]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF941CFCFB6A9A0BFA99" box="[430,573,1262,1288]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">C. japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="C52466A8BF54FF941F38FB699B2FFA96" author="Guignot, F." box="[618,793,1261,1288]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" pagination="17 - 31" refId="ref32148" refString="Guignot, F. (1952) Description de dytiscides inedits de la collection Regimbart. Revue Francaise d'Entomologie, 19, 17 - 31." type="journal article" year="1952">Guignot (1952)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="C52466A8BF54FF941E01FB699BEEFA96" author="Sato, M." box="[851,984,1261,1288]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" pagination="57 - 67" refId="ref33445" refString="Sato, M. (1985) The genus Copelatus of Japan (Coleoptera: Dytiscidae). Transactions of the Shikoku Entomological Society, 17, 57 - 67." type="journal article" year="1985">Satô (1985)</bibRefCitation>
respectively. However, the study of the 
<typeStatus id="7E0EA5FBBF54FF941DC5FA9698F1FAB2" box="[151,199,1298,1324]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF54FF941C19FA9699E5FAB5" authorityName="Regimbart" authorityYear="1899" box="[331,467,1297,1324]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="chinensis">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF941C19FA9699E5FAB5" box="[331,467,1297,1324]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">C. chinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
proved that it is a valid species separate from 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF54FF941E9FFA969C6FFAB5" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1884" box="[973,1113,1298,1324]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF941E9FFA969C6FFAB5" box="[973,1113,1298,1324]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">C. japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, while the extensive material collected recently in various localities in southern 
<collectingCountry id="D9A25BC9BF54FF941F83FAB19B22FAD1" box="[721,788,1333,1359]" name="China" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">China</collectingCountry>
belongs to numerous taxa new to science. At present, we are aware of only a single reliable record of 
<taxonomicName id="66B560DABF54FF941FD4FADE9B22FAED" authorityName="Sharp" authorityYear="1884" box="[646,788,1370,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Dytiscidae" genus="Copelatus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonicus">
<emphasis id="93C1C74BBF54FF941FD4FADE9B22FAED" box="[646,788,1370,1396]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">C. japonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="D9A25BC9BF54FF941E0AFADD9BADFAED" box="[856,923,1369,1395]" name="China" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">China</collectingCountry>
– 
<collectingRegion id="6371D5BBBF54FF941EE5FADD9C14FAED" box="[951,1058,1369,1395]" country="China" name="Shanghai" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">Shanghai</collectingRegion>
, presented above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E9AF48D2BF54FF941D95FAF99D34FA09" box="[199,1282,1405,1432]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="A10A1B59BF54FF941D95FAF99D34FA09" blockId="9.[151,1437,577,1432]" box="[199,1282,1405,1432]" pageId="9" pageNumber="260">
